<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>BIODIVERSITY OFFSETTING</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h1 style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from the Environment, Food and Rural Affairs</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> Committee</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> (SCE0021)</span></h1><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:MinionPro-It; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The EFRA Committee examines the administration, expenditure and policy of the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs. This memorandum is intended to outline its work since 2012-13 to show how it has responded to the recommendations for Select Committees contained in the Liaison Committee’s report on</span><span style="font-family:MinionPro-It; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> Select committee effectiveness, resources and powers</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:MinionPro-It; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Committee has produced 14 reports since 2012-13, six in the present session; a full list is attached to this note.  Rather than provide an exhaustive commentary on their contents, we offer examples of where our work has met the Liaison Committee’s aspirations.</span></li></ol><h3 style="margin:6pt 0pt 12pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Effectiveness</span></h3><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Liaison Committee identified influence and impact on Government policy as the primary measure of a committee’s effectiveness. Two of the Committee’s key achievements in that respect relate to its pre-legislative scrutiny work on the draft Water Bill and draft Dangerous Dogs legislation (Core task 4).</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Committee produced a full report on the draft Water Bill, its recommendations feeding into substantial revisions before the Water Bill obtained its first reading in July, and the Committee intends to continue to track the Bill’s progress through the House and to offer amendments if and when appropriate (Core task 9).  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Committee was pleased that its inquiry into Dangerous Dogs legislation fed into the Government’s development of new clauses enabling, among other things, exemption from prosecution for owners whose dogs attack burglars. We were less pleased to be asked by Defra to scrutinise those clauses in fewer than 10 parliamentary days. None the less, we responded swiftly and obtained changes in the draft clauses by highlighting points made during a one-off oral evidence session; the principal change was a widening of the definition of who might be considered exempt. The clauses, contained in the Anti-Social Behaviour, Crime and Policing Bill, are now before the House of Lords.</span></li></ol><h3 style="margin:6pt 0pt 12pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Strategic planning</span></h3><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Liaison Committee recommended that Committees take stock of achievements to date and agree their objectives for the remainder of this Parliament. The EFRA Committee held an ‘awayday’ in April to, among other things, set a strategy for its work until May 2015 and consider its methods of work. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Committee made use of an external facilitator (from the institute of Government) to aid the discussion on ways of working or improving effectiveness.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We have not, as recommended, published a set of strategic objectives, but we have identified two major strands of Defra’s work – reform of the Common Agricultural Policy and the need to maintain Food Security – as the foci of our major inquiries during the coming 12 months.  It is our intention to use the space around those inquiries to scrutinise new policy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">proposals, follow up on our own previous work and hold one-off evidence sessions on matters of immediate interest. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We also agreed, in principle, to use a sub-committee model as and when appropriate to enable the Committee to consider quickly discrete subjects on an ad hoc basis at times when the full Committee is engaged in a major inquiry.  We have not yet put that into practice, but will consider doing so as topics arise in 2014 and 2015.</span></li></ol><h3 style="margin:6pt 0pt 12pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Follow-up work</span></h3><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Liaison Committee stressed the importance of Committees’ following up their recommendations. We have, throughout the present Parliament, demonstrated an eagerness to follow up our work – we have produced series of reports on CAP and issues related to Water and Flooding, for example, and produced follow-up reports.  We have also, in the case of the horsemeat contamination discovered last year, found it useful to report on an interim basis in response to an emergency, giving an indication of urgent actions required, and then to produce a second, more considered report in due course (see our reports on Meat Contamination and Food Contamination, and the Government’s responses, which in turn followed our reactive inquiry into a government moratorium on the use of Desinewed Meat).  The same case demonstrates another means of follow-up: we sought a debate in Westminster Hall in October 2014 on both reports, and will continue to monitor developments in the role of the Food Standards Agency and allied matters.</span></li></ol><h3 style="margin:6pt 0pt 12pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Core tasks</span></h3><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Committee welcomes the revised list of core tasks published by the Liaison Committee, which remain a useful framework for organising the work the Committee must undertake. The following is not intended to be a comprehensive analysis of our work vis-a-vis each task, but to indicate key connections with the list.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In scrutinising Defra’s policy objectives and priorities, we have sought to mix our approach, both focusing on individual policy proposals as they arise and providing more thematic investigations into major areas within the department’s remit.  Our work in the former respect is exemplified by our reports on the Natural Environment White Paper or on Meat Contamination and Food Contamination.  Our more general, thematic scrutiny of the Department is represented by, for example, our reports on Rural Communities and repeated reports on aspects of the Common Agricultural Policy.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As previously noted, we have pre-legislatively scrutinised several draft Bills (Water, Dangerous Dogs and Wild Animals in Circuses), and we have sought further to assist the House by promoting amendments to Dangerous Dogs legislation, a practice we plan to repeat with the Water Bill, if required.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We held a pre-appointment hearing with the new Chair of Ofwat in July 2012 and intend to do so when the preferred candidate for the Chair of Natural England is established soon.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We have routinely sought to ‘tag’ our reports to relevant debates in Westminster Hall and the House (for example, our report on Bovine TB Vaccination was frequently referred to during the House’s most recent Back Bench debate on badger culling). We have also obtained Westminster Hall debates on Dangerous Dogs and Meat Contamination.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In terms of public engagement, many of the areas we cover garner considerable public interest – the horsemeat scandal, flooding events and badger culling give a flavour of both the range and often highly emotive nature of the subject matter within Defra’s ambit.  We have been successful in obtaining wide media coverage for most of our significant inquiries, and we have sought directly to obtain coverage in both the trade and local press and, in particular, in local radio broadcast in geographical areas where our subject matter is of specific local interest.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We will continue to use the task list as a guide for organising the work we do during the remainder of this Parliament.  We shall also continue to seek means of further implementing the best practice guidance contained in the Liaison Committee’s effectiveness report, with an emphasis in that regard on continuing to improve our media planning and strategy, broadening the range of witnesses with whom we engage and following up the recommendations made both in this and in the 2005 Parliaments. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">29 October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>